    "articles-01": {
  id: "articles-01",
  category: "UI/UX Design",
  title: "Playable Learning Interface",
  link: "/game/index.html",
  images: [
    "../projects/articles-01/img1.jpg",
    "../projects/articles-01/img2.jpg",
    "../projects/articles-01/img3.jpg"
  ],
  description: `Playable Learning Interface is a browser-based interactive prototype that explores how educational or informational content can be delivered through movement, scene transition, and level-based discovery rather than static reading. The project reframes a typically passive process as a playable experience, encouraging users to navigate forward, uncover new content, and remain engaged through progression.

The system was developed with a modular p5.js and WebGL pipeline that separates rendering, world logic, player behavior, shader control, and asset loading into dedicated files. A custom ZIP-based loader manages models, fonts, images, and JSON data, while a structured level system controls progression, transitions, and scene organization inside the browser.

Interaction is built around character navigation, collision logic, key-and-door mechanics, stairs, goal triggers, and two parallel world states that can be visually switched through screen-based transitions. This structure supports wayfinding as both a gameplay mechanic and a UX device, guiding users through content by combining spatial exploration with clear progression cues.

Visually, the project uses a custom shader and post-processing workflow with palette-based rendering, dithering, framebuffer passes, and lightweight visual effects to maintain clarity, performance, and stylistic consistency. The result is a compact but technically layered prototype that demonstrates interaction design, gamification, front-end creative coding, and the ability to translate abstract content into a readable, playable user experience.`,
  text: `Playable Learning Interface is a browser-based interactive prototype that explores how educational or informational content can be delivered through movement, scene transition, and level-based discovery rather than static reading. The project reframes a typically passive process as a playable experience, encouraging users to navigate forward, uncover new content, and remain engaged through progression.

The system was developed with a modular p5.js and WebGL pipeline that separates rendering, world logic, player behavior, shader control, and asset loading into dedicated files. A custom ZIP-based loader manages models, fonts, images, and JSON data, while a structured level system controls progression, transitions, and scene organization inside the browser.

Interaction is built around character navigation, collision logic, key-and-door mechanics, stairs, goal triggers, and two parallel world states that can be visually switched through screen-based transitions. This structure supports wayfinding as both a gameplay mechanic and a UX device, guiding users through content by combining spatial exploration with clear progression cues.

Visually, the project uses a custom shader and post-processing workflow with palette-based rendering, dithering, framebuffer passes, and lightweight visual effects to maintain clarity, performance, and stylistic consistency. The result is a compact but technically layered prototype that demonstrates interaction design, gamification, front-end creative coding, and the ability to translate abstract content into a readable, playable user experience.`
},

