  description: `Depth Cues in Immersive VR Interfaces presents a research-driven investigation into how color, luminance, and transparency influence perceived depth in head-mounted displays. Developed through a user-centered experimental workflow, the project connects immersive interface design with spatial cognition, interaction accuracy, and the visual logic required to build more legible virtual environments.

The study was designed and developed from concept to publication, including literature review, experimental framing, scene construction, test condition design, participant evaluation, statistical analysis, and academic writing. Using Unreal Engine 4.27, Meta Oculus Quest 2, Blueprint-based interaction, and controlled VR stimuli, the research tested multiple transparency, color, and luminance conditions through a forced-choice pairwise comparison method with sixty participants.

Beyond technical development, the work demonstrates the ability to translate design questions into measurable research outcomes. Data collection and matrix construction were organized through structured evaluation workflows, and the results were interpreted using Kendall’s coefficient of agreement and consistency to identify perceptual patterns across conditions. The findings revealed that high transparency levels can reverse classical expectations of warm/cool color and bright/dark luminance as depth cues in VR.

This project reflects a practice that moves across UI/UX design, immersive environment design, research methodology, and scholarly communication. It demonstrates not only the ability to build interactive VR experiments from scratch, but also to frame user-centered design problems, analyze perception systematically, and communicate design knowledge through a professional research publication.`,
